The paper deals with computational problems related to bribery in elections, which falls under the category of computational social choice theory (cs.GT). The use of frugal bribery and the formulation of new computational problems suggest a focus on algorithmic solutions, which could fall under artificial intelligence (cs.AI) or algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The study of computational complexity also suggests a focus on theoretical computer science, which could fall under machine learning (cs.LG) or computational complexity (cs.CC).
